Today, we will get to know another famous renju player. Some of you may be have heard of him or even seen him.
We will learn about a guy who once was very powerful player, he even won the Youth World Championship many years ago.
Maris is about 6 years younger than margus, his sister
Maris Tuvikene was a participant in last female WC
but Margus does not play much renju nowadays,
Margus and I began to play renju in about same time, in the same club
he had quite good progress at that time too
One of the peaks of his career in adults tournament was the year 1991,
when he was successful player in Russian first league.
ahead of Nikolay Mihailov and me,
and ahead some more strong players.
In the last rounds he was not so successful,
But Russian First league was one of the strongest tournaments in the world
in fact, that tournament is even stronger than the finals of other countrys national championships.
Todays game, though, comes from the Russian First league that was played one year before that, in 1990 in Simferopol.
you know the big changes in 1991,
so, in 1990, the USSR still existed.
And the Russian First league took place in first league,
10 best from first league qualified to high league
no much idea about these places :)
the peninsular of Krym is in Black Sea
Margus has even won Igor Synov 3.5-0.5 in same tournament (team WC 1996). Correct, Ando?
So, we start with the game now,
he was busy with his studies,
So, we will look at his game now , played 13 years ago in Simferopol
13 years ago, when  he is just 12 yeras olr??
not surprising at all, at that time.
Estonia has many young renju stars in history
at that time, tentative white plays 2nd move?
since 1988 already the RIF rule was established
thats why i1 is frequently played :)
it was hard to find a good balance among indirect openings
so we saw openings like i1, i5, i11, i10, i8 a lot
actually i11 and i10 were very balanced at that time,
because people did not know much about best possible moves,
So far, it is a known theoretical variant.
As we all know from theory,
the optimal move may seem j9,
Then the black space here is too narrow
it is all because of rotated 4th move
and foresaw this problem of edge,
where would you put the 10th move, up or down?
maybe down is more  attack for white?
so many of you say up,
more choices to attack for black there
i think it needs some longer explanation
up is passive, but maybe safe, b is so powerful there
because powerful itself is not enough argument,
you must also consider, who has tempo,
and if that power is dangerous
and compare whites own possibilities in long perspective etc
if Nakamura was here, he would not just think the seemingly dangerous power in first sight,
but trying to see if the power is really dangerous,
and how far that attack might go
and how would white stand in the end,
and when can white get the tempo
I see immediately that black has no immediate win plan if i play 10 down
actually black power is not so strong as first look
for me, the 10 up is a question
even if i calculate all branches
and find out that 10 down is safe too
then i must make the final decision by comparing the outcomes,
that the 10-h12 outcome is better for white
but i am not so sure about it myself
Just afraid of black by feeling :)
to give better answer, would need more thinking time....
after all, you all may be right
and maybe that game will also confirm your feeling
anyway, i just explained how to think rationally,
we can make sure that both ends can be defended,
and then we make decision by not from the aspect of danger, but from the aspect of our own benefit
Maybe 10-L8 is giving more benefit for white,
because then black cannot easily come to lower area later
so white will ensure at least one promising area for future
which will help white to win, to avoid draw
Perhaps here, black can somehow use positional style,
and carefully fill up the board.
but you should think this way at least
then you will win more games
As you know, great Nakamura always thinks it
as you remember from my first game with him
but in overall calculation, the defense was not an issue,
so he eventually chose between bigger benefit
but this tells you one important thing:
there are no good or bad defenses
if it defends, then its sufficient
and if we can have many choices,
we choose the one that is best for ourselves later
in that regard, move 20-L7 is better defense than 20-h11
He likely estimated that black cannot win,
then in the long run white will benefit more from lower 10th move
ok lets see what happened then.
How Margus skilfully took advantage of al black potential
Margus did not play h12 first
why didnt margus play h12 first
if white goes there now, then black has very good chances
the rule of playing a four, who remembers?
1. we play a four when we have VCF
2. we play a four if it is necessary for defense
3. we play a four if we are afraid that white takes that point
and assume white might take h12
I can win, but not in 5..
I also need more moves. maybe someone show us less moves
finding win is quite good already I think :)
anyway, it is win. moves is not so important.
So, if white cannot take h12,
no need to make a four
no need to use the four
because black doesnt have vcf now,
and no unrgent defense related to the four
and no fear that white would take that point
if we dont play the four NOW,
we can always play it LATER if we want
For example, now black can play h12 too if he wants,
maybe even four to g13 might be good someday
or, h12 will be a nice 4x3 point
knowing exactly what fours should be played and what not
Gorshenkov was a strong player too at that time.
